Football_Win

Tarun Reddy Aleti

February 29, 2016

Executive Summary

  • The data set at hand covers all the “Serie A” football matches for the last 8 years of Italian Football League.
  • Our goal is to predict the final result, having at your disposal the odds of various bookmakers.
  • Need to use 6 years of data and predict the result for next 2 years.
  • Best model is the one which predicts accurately more often.
  • The dataset for the model can be downloaded from train, test

Preliminary Analysis

For the code to execute, all the datasets should be in the R working directory. The datasets are in .csv format.

set.seed(1)
data <- read.csv("train.csv", header = TRUE, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
  • The data set under consideration has a total of 1520 rows and 21 independent variables. Our dependent variable is FTR (Full Time Result) and is a categorical variable, wherein A indicates that Away team won, H indicates that home team won and D indicates that result was a draw

  • Independent Variables are as follows

    1. Date: Indicates when the match was played
      • Can extract Weekday/Weekend, DayofWeek and Month information
    2. HomeTeam: Name of Home Team in the match
      • There are 27 different teams. We might need to create dummy variables for them.
      • The team names are Sampdoria, Verona, Cagliari, Inter, Lazio, Livorno, Napoli, Parma, Torino, Fiorentina, Chievo, Juventus, Atalanta, Bologna, Catania, Genoa, Milan, Roma, Sassuolo, Udinese, Palermo, Lecce, Reggina, Siena, Bari, Cesena, Brescia.
    3. AwayTeam: Name of Away Team in the match
      • There are 27 different teams. We might need to create dummy variables for them.
      • The team names are Juventus, Milan, Atalanta, Genoa, Udinese, Roma, Bologna, Chievo, Sassuolo, Catania, Napoli, Lazio, Torino, Sampdoria, Inter, Fiorentina, Cagliari, Verona, Livorno, Parma, Palermo, Siena, Reggina, Lecce, Bari, Cesena, Brescia.
      • There are same number of Home Teams as Away Teams
    4. B365H: Bet365 home win odds
    5. B365D: Bet365 draw odds
  1. B365A: Bet365 away win odds
  2. BWH: Bet&Win home win odds
  3. BWD: Bet&Win draw odds
  4. BWA: Bet&Win away win odds
  5. IWH: Interwetten home win odds
  6. IWD: Interwetten draw odds
  7. IWA: Interwetten away win odds
  8. LBH: Ladbrokes home win odds
  9. LBD: Ladbrokes draw odds
  10. LBA: Ladbrokes away win odds
  11. VCH: VC Bet home win odds
  12. VCD: VC Bet draw odds
  13. VCA: VC Bet away win odds
  14. WHH: William Hill home win odds
  15. WHD: William Hill draw odds
  16. WHA: William Hill away win odds

Dummy Variables

First we need to create dummy variables for all the categorical variables like HomeTeam, AwayTeam, Month, DayofWeek and DayType

fac_var <- c("HomeTeam", "AwayTeam", "Month", "DayofWeek", "DayType")

for(var in fac_var){
    data[ ,var] <- as.factor(data[ ,var])
}

dumm_var <- fac_var
final_data <- data[ ,setdiff(colnames(data), c(dumm_var, "ID"))]

for(dumm in dumm_var){
    dumm_data <- model.matrix( ~ data[ ,dumm] - 1, data = data)
    colnames(dumm_data) <- paste(dumm, gsub("data|, dumm|[[:punct:]]", "", colnames(dumm_data)), sep = "_")
    final_data <- cbind(final_data, dumm_data)
}

colnames(final_data) <- gsub(" ", "", colnames(final_data))
final_data$FTR <- as.factor(final_data$FTR)

Missing data - Data Imputation

The bid odds have data missing with 3 for Bet365, 15 for Bet&Win, 16 for InterWetten, 5 for Ladbrokes and 6 for WilliamHill and 19 for VC Bet. We need to impute data for each of them.

for(bet in colnames(final_data)[3:20]){
  missing_bet <- data[(is.na(final_data[ ,bet])), ]
  for(i in 1:dim(missing_bet)[1]){
    x <- data[data$HomeTeam == missing_bet[i, 'HomeTeam'] & data$AwayTeam == missing_bet[i, 'AwayTeam'], ]
    if(dim(x)[1] == 1){
      x <- data[(data$HomeTeam == missing_bet[i, 'HomeTeam'] | data$AwayTeam == missing_bet[i, 'AwayTeam']) & year(data$Date) == year(missing_bet[i, 'Date']), ]
    }
    x$rate <- 1
    x[x[ ,'FTR'] == missing_bet[i, 'FTR'], 'rate'] <- 2
    final_data[which(is.na(data[ ,bet]))[i], bet] <- sum(x$rate * x[ ,bet], na.rm = TRUE)/sum(x$rate, na.rm = TRUE)
  }
}

Used other records available for same home team and away team and imputed using weighted mean of the data where data with same result is given twice the weightage compared with other data.

Near Zero Variance

We need not consider independent variables which do not enough variance in itself. We can use nzv of caret package for this analysis. Following 31 variables have near zero variance and we need not consider them further: HomeTeam_Atalanta, HomeTeam_Bari, HomeTeam_Brescia, HomeTeam_Cesena, HomeTeam_Lecce, HomeTeam_Livorno, HomeTeam_Palermo, HomeTeam_Parma, HomeTeam_Reggina, HomeTeam_Sassuolo, HomeTeam_Siena, HomeTeam_Torino, HomeTeam_Verona, AwayTeam_Atalanta, AwayTeam_Bari, AwayTeam_Brescia, AwayTeam_Cesena, AwayTeam_Lecce, AwayTeam_Livorno, AwayTeam_Palermo, AwayTeam_Parma, AwayTeam_Reggina, AwayTeam_Sassuolo, AwayTeam_Siena, AwayTeam_Torino, AwayTeam_Verona, Month_Aug, DayofWeek_Mon, DayofWeek_Tue, DayofWeek_Thu, DayofWeek_Fri

nzv_var <- nzv(final_data)
final_data <- final_data[ ,-nzv_var]

Creating Train and Test Samples

  • We have a total of 1520 rows and 60 independent variables. Now that we have a clean data set before we head to modeling, we need to create a train and test data sets. Since we need to eventually predict on 2 years of data we can use 4 years to train (2008 to 2011) and 2 year to test (2013 and 2014).
train <- final_data[year(final_data$Date) < 2013, -1]
test <- final_data[year(final_data$Date) >= 2013, -1]
  • Size of train data set is 1140 and test data set is 380

The first three principal components explain the variance present in all the 18 variables. First factor describes preference of home team winning against draw or losing (all the home bids have high positive value, while draw and away have low values), second factor shows home team not winning against draw or losing (home bids have negative value, while draw or away have high positive values), third factor shows preference for draw or away team winning (only draw and away have mostly positive values). We can define these components as StrongHome, StrongDrawWeakAway and WeakDrawStrongAway.

train[ ,c('StrongHome', 'StrongDrawWeakAway', 'WeakDrawStrongAway')] <- data.matrix(train[ ,c(2:19)]) %*% data.matrix(fit$loadings[ ,c('PC1', 'PC2', 'PC3')])
test[ ,c('StrongHome', 'StrongDrawWeakAway', 'WeakDrawStrongAway')] <- data.matrix(test[ ,c(2:19)]) %*% data.matrix(fit$loadings[ ,c('PC1', 'PC2', 'PC3')])

Collinearity Diagnostics

Before moving to modeling, we need to make sure that none of our independent variables have a collinearity among themselves. One way to ensure this is using the Variance Influence Factor. In general any value greater than 10 is considered high collinearity. (Note: Source for below vif_func function).

vif_func <- function(in_frame, thresh=10, trace=T){
    #get initial vif value for all comparisons of variables
    vif_init<-NULL
    var_names <- names(in_frame)
    for(val in var_names){
        regressors <- var_names[-which(var_names == val)]
        form <- paste(regressors, collapse = '+')
        form_in <- formula(paste(val, '~', form))
        vif_init<-rbind(vif_init, c(val, VIF(lm(form_in, data = in_frame))))
    }
    vif_init <- vif_init[!is.nan(as.numeric(vif_init[ ,2])), ]
    vif_max<-max(as.numeric(vif_init[,2]))
    if(vif_max >= thresh){
        in_dat<-in_frame
        #backwards selection of explanatory variables, stops when all VIF values are below 'thresh'
        while(vif_max >= thresh){
            vif_vals<-NULL
            var_names <- names(in_dat)
            for(val in var_names){
                regressors <- var_names[-which(var_names == val)]
                form <- paste(regressors, collapse = '+')
                form_in <- formula(paste(val, '~', form))
                vif_add<-VIF(lm(form_in, data = in_dat))
                vif_vals<-rbind(vif_vals,c(val,vif_add))
            }
            max_row<-which(vif_vals[,2] == max(as.numeric(vif_vals[,2])))[1]
            vif_vals <- vif_vals[!is.nan(as.numeric(vif_vals[ ,2])), ]
            vif_max<-as.numeric(vif_vals[max_row,2])
            if(vif_max<thresh) break
            in_dat<-in_dat[,!names(in_dat) %in% vif_vals[max_row,1]]

        }
    return(names(in_dat))
    }
}

final_vars <- vif_func(in_frame = train[ ,-1])

4 independent variables DayofWeek_Sat, DayType_Weekday, StrongHome, WeakDrawStrongAway that were found to have high collinearity.

train <- train[ ,c('FTR', final_vars)]
test <- test[ ,c('FTR', final_vars)]
